    title: 'The Heliopolitan Creation (Atum)',
    civilization: 'Ancient Egypt',
    dateRange: '3100–332 BCE',
    summary: `From Nun, the infinite dark ocean, the self-created god Atum rose upon the first mound and brought forth the first divine pair from his own body. Their offspring became air and moisture, then earth and sky, unfolding the Ennead and the ordered Egyptian cosmos.`,
    fullText: `In the Egyptian Heliopolitan tradition, before the world existed there was only Nun — the primordial, endless, dark ocean of chaos and potential. From within these formless waters, Atum (the "complete one") came into being through his own will, standing atop the first solid ground: the benben stone or primordial mound.

Alone and without partner, Atum created the first divine pair through himself — Shu (air) and Tefnut (moisture) — by spitting or by an act of masturbation. Shu and Tefnut then coupled to produce Geb (the earth) and Nut (the sky). Nut arched over Geb in a great embrace until Shu separated them, lifting Nut up to become the heavens while Geb lay flat as the earth.

From Geb and Nut came the four great gods: Osiris, Isis, Set, and Nephthys — the Ennead of Heliopolis. Ra, the sun god, was sometimes identified with Atum as Ra-Atum, sailing each day across the sky in his solar barque and descending into the underworld each night to be reborn at dawn.`,
