    summary: `The Rigveda's Purusha Sukta describes the cosmos as born from the sacrifice of Purusha, the primordial cosmic Person. From his dismembered body came the sun, moon, sky, and earth — and the four social orders — making the whole structured world a single willing sacrifice.`,
    fullText: `The Purusha Sukta is one of the most celebrated hymns of the Rigveda (10.90). It describes Purusha — the Cosmic Person or Primordial Being — as a being of a thousand heads, a thousand eyes, and a thousand feet, pervading the entire earth and extending ten fingers beyond it.

Three-quarters of Purusha is immortal and dwells in the heavens; only one-quarter became the visible world. From this one-quarter arose all living creatures. The gods performed a great sacrifice (yajna), offering Purusha himself as the oblation.

From the clarified butter of this cosmic sacrifice came the birds, the animals of forest and field, and the three Vedas. From his mind came the Moon; from his eye, the Sun; from his mouth, Indra and Agni; from his breath, Vayu the wind. The sky arose from his navel, the heavens from his head, the earth from his feet, and the four directions from his ears.

From this same sacrifice arose the four varnas (social orders): the Brahmin from his mouth, the Kshatriya from his arms, the Vaishya from his thighs, and the Shudra from his feet. The entire structured cosmos — social, natural, and divine — is thus an expression of a single primordial, willing sacrifice.`,
