  akkadian: {
    id: 'akkadian',
    title: 'The Atrahasis Epic — Creation and the Great Flood',
    civilization: 'Akkadian Empire',
    dateRange: '2334–2154 BCE',
    summary: `In the Atrahasis Epic, the gods make humans from clay mixed with a slain god's blood to labor in their place. When humankind grows too numerous and loud the gods send plague, drought, and finally a great Flood — survived only by Atrahasis, warned by Enki to build a boat.`,
    fullText: `The Atrahasis Epic (also spelled Atra-Hasis, meaning "exceedingly wise") is an Akkadian-language mythological narrative known from tablets dating to approximately 1700 BCE, though the traditions it records are considerably older. It is arguably the most complete early account of both the creation of humanity and the great flood.

In the beginning, the gods were divided into two classes: the great gods (the Anunnaki) who ruled, and the lesser gods (the Igigi) who performed all the labor — digging rivers, hauling earth. After 3,600 years, the Igigi rebelled. Exhausted and furious, they burned their tools and surrounded the palace of Enlil, chief of the gods.

The god Enki proposed a solution: create a new being to perform the labor. The mother goddess Mami (or Ninhursag) mixed clay with the blood and flesh of a god who had instigated the rebellion. From this divine-clay mixture, she fashioned the first humans — Lullu, "the primitive one." Humanity was made to bear the yoke of the gods: to till fields, dig canals, build temples, and provide offerings.

The plan succeeded — but too well. Humanity multiplied rapidly. Within a few centuries, their noise and clamor disturbed the sleep of the god Enlil, who could not rest. Enlil called upon the gods to send pestilence. Humans suffered greatly, but Enki secretly advised the wise king Atrahasis to appease the plague god with offerings, and the plague passed. Enlil tried again with drought, and then famine. Each time, Enki found a way to circumvent Enlil's plan and help Atrahasis save humanity.

Finally, Enlil persuaded the assembly of gods to send the Flood, binding all gods — including Enki — with an oath of secrecy. But Enki spoke not to Atrahasis directly, but to the reed fence of his house: "Wall, listen! Dismantling your house, build a boat." Atrahasis built the boat, loaded it with animals and provisions, and survived seven days and seven nights of flood while the gods themselves cowered from the destruction they had made.

When the flood receded, Atrahasis made offerings. The gods — who had not eaten during the flood — swarmed over the food like flies. The goddess Mami wept for the humanity she had created. A compromise was reached: henceforth, infant mortality, infertility, and natural death would control human numbers, so the gods could rest.`,
    category: 'chaos-combat',
    themes: ['flood', 'creation-from-body', 'sacrifice', 'water', 'hero'],
    relatedTexts: [
      { title: 'Atra-Hasis: The Babylonian Story of the Flood', author: 'W.G. Lambert & A.R. Millard', type: 'Critical edition (Oxford, 1969)', url: '' },
      { title: 'Myths from Mesopotamia', author: 'Stephanie Dalley (trans.)', type: 'Translation (Oxford, 1989)', url: '' },
      { title: 'Atra-Hasis (Wikipedia)', author: '', type: 'Reference', url: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atra-Hasis' },
    ],
    imageUrl: '',
  },

